2 HOUSE BILL 315
1 WHEREAS, In the ensuing 248 years, methods for holding and transmitting wealth
2 have changed significantly, and probate and fiduciary legal issues have become
3 substantially more complex; and
4 WHEREAS, The General Assembly recognizes the value that a specialized court
5 brings to families in times of transition; and
6 WHEREAS, The General Assembly also recognizes the need for further changes to
7 fiduciary adjudication in Maryland in order to provide a uniform and efficient system for
8 its citizens; now, therefore,
9 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
10 That:
11 (a) There is a Task Force to Study Fiduciary Adjudication in Maryland.
12 (b) The Task Force consists of the following members:
13 (1) two members of the Senate of Maryland, appointed by the President of
14 the Senate;
15 (2) two members of the House of Delegates, appointed by the Speaker of
16 the House;
17 (3) two members who are judges of an orphans’ court, at least one of whom
18 serves in a jurisdiction where orphans’ court judges are required to be attorneys, appointed
19 by the chair of the Conference of Orphans’ Court Judges;
20 (4) one member who is a judge of the circuit court in a jurisdiction where
21 the circuit court sits as the orphans’ court, appointed by the Chief Justice of the Supreme
22 Court of Maryland;
23 (5) two members of the Maryland State Bar Association, designated by the
24 chair of the Estate and Trust Law Section Council, at least one of whom is who between
25 them shall include a fiduciary litigator and a resident of a jurisdiction with a population of
26 less than 250,000;
27 (6) the chair two registers of wills designated by the president of the
28 Maryland Register of Wills Association; and
29 (7) one member with expertise in budgeting and personnel matters,
30 appointed by the Governor.
31 (c) The Governor shall designate the chair of the Task Force from among the
32 members appointed by the President of the Senate or the Speaker of the House.

HOUSE BILL 315 3
1 (d) The Administrative Office of the Courts shall provide staff for the Task Force.
2 (e) A member of the Task Force:
3 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Task Force; but
4 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
5 Travel Regulations, as provided in the State budget.
6 (f) The Task Force shall:
7 (1) examine the qualifications, training, and methods of selection of judges
8 hearing probate and other fiduciary matters in Maryland;
9 (2) examine the jurisdictions of the orphans’ courts and circuit courts with
10 respect to fiduciary matters;
11 (3) analyze the efficiency of the procedures for adjudicating fiduciary
12 matters in the orphans’ courts and circuit courts;
13 (4) analyze the effect of the different qualifications of orphans’ court judges
14 and related litigation procedures on the uniform application of justice in Maryland;
15 (5) analyze and compare the laws and practices of other states relating to
16 the adjudication of fiduciary matters, including the selection, qualification, and training of
17 judges hearing those matters;
18 (6) seek guidance from appropriate witnesses with experience or expertise
19 in the area of fiduciary adjudication;
20 (7) examine any other research, analysis, or guidance related to the best
21 practices for adjudicating fiduciary matters;
22 (8) offer one or more opportunities for members of the public and other
23 interested parties to give their opinions on the subjects considered by the Task Force; and
24 (9) make recommendations to improve efficiency, uniformity, and quality
25 of fiduciary adjudication in Maryland.
26 (g) The orphans’ courts, circuit courts, registers of wills, and Administrative
27 Office of the Courts shall comply with all reasonable requests by the Task Force for
28 information and data the Task Force considers necessary for its work.
29 (h) On or before January 1, 2026, the Task Force shall report its findings and
30 recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State
31 Government Article, the General Assembly.

